<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1438,726,1255]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,834,859]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The habitus of this species (
<figureCitation box="[783,864,834,858]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–19" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[252,1331,206,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-102@16.[231,1356,195,1707]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 16–19. Epimetopus holotypes, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) is very similar to that of several other members of the 
<emphasis box="[198,296,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Costatus</emphasis>
group; reliable determinations will be based on examination of the aedeagus. The aedeagus is somewhat similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Oliva" authorityYear="1986" box="[475,587,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hintoni">
<emphasis box="[475,587,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">E. hintoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[605,700,906,930]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–15" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1641,1664]" captionTargetBox="[175,1414,226,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-73@14.[151,1436,195,1619]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 12–15. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs. 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[714,745,906,930]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–23" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1672,1695]" captionTargetBox="[256,1332,191,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[227,1360,167,1679]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 20–23. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">21</figureCitation>
). However, the median lobe is slightly wider than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Oliva" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hintoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">E. hintoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas the parameres, in both views, are narrower. The median lobe internal structures also differ in the two species, as illustrated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1438,726,1255]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,344,1014,1039]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1014,1039]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Description</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Size: 
<typeStatus box="[421,519,1014,1038]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length from anterior margin of pronotum to elytral apices) 1.56/0.75; head (width) 0.40; pronotum 0.56/0.57; elytra 1.01/0.75. Habitus and sculpture as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[159,246,1086,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–19" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[252,1331,206,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-102@16.[231,1356,195,1707]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 16–19. Epimetopus holotypes, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Head black, dorsum red, venter and coxae dark brown, maxillary palpi testaceous. Eye with ca. 4–5 facets between canthus and posterior margin. Elytra with distinct granules linking punctures. Protibiae slightly arcuate. Metaventral depression moderately deep, ca. eight granules along base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
